{"title_page": "Harold Connolly", "text_new": "{{For|the American athlete|Hal Connolly}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Harold Connolly\n| birthname        = Harold&nbsp;Joseph&nbsp;Connolly\n| image            =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=yes|1901|9|8}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1980|5|17|1901|9|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place      =\n| spouse           = {{hlist|Catherine&nbsp;Burns&nbsp;(m.&nbsp;1928)|Vivian Martel}}\n| residence        =\n| office1          = [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly|MLA]] for [[Halifax North]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Gordon Benjamin Isnor]]\n| successor1       = [[John E. Ahern]]\n| term_start1      = March 2, 1936\n| term_end1        = July 28, 1955\n| office           = 15th [[Premier of Nova Scotia]]\n| predecessor      = [[Angus Lewis Macdonald|Angus L. Macdonald]]\n| successor        = [[Henry Hicks (Nova Scotia politician)|Henry Hicks]]\n| term_start       = April 14, 1954\n| term_end         = September 29, 1954\n| monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| lieutenant_governor= [[Alistair Fraser]]\n| office2          = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for Halifax North, Nova Scotia\n| appointed2       = [[Louis St. Laurent]]\n| term_start2      = July 28, 1955\n| term_end2        = May 14, 1979\n| profession       = editor, journalist\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| website          =\n}}\n'''Harold Joseph Connolly''' (8 September 1901 \u2013 17 May 1980) was a [[Nova Scotia]] journalist, newspaper editor, and politician who served as the province's [[List of premiers of Nova Scotia|15th Premier]] in 1954.\n\nConnolly was born in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]], the son of Richard Joseph Connolly and Annie Duffield. He was educated at St. Mary's College. As a newspaperman, he worked for the ''[[The Chronicle Herald|Halifax Chronicle]]'' before serving as editor of the ''Daily Star''.\n\nHe was first elected to the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] in a 1936 by-election as a [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party|Liberal]] in [[Halifax North]] after [[Gordon Benjamin Isnor]] was elected to the House of Commons. He was appointed to cabinet in 1941 as Minister of Industry and Publicity. He served as Minister of Industry and Trade from 1945 to 1950, when he became Minister of Public Health. When Premier [[Angus Lewis Macdonald|Angus L. Macdonald]] died in 1954, Connolly became the province's premier and the Liberal party's [[Interim leader (Canada)|interim leader]]. A [[Catholic]], he was defeated by [[Henry Hicks (Nova Scotia politician)|Henry Hicks]] at the party's [[leadership convention]] when [[Protestant]] delegates formed a united front against a Catholic leader, a move that caused a severe religious split within the party that contributed to its defeat two years later at the hands of [[Robert Stanfield]]'s [[Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservatives]].\n\nConnolly retired from provincial politics in 1955 when he was elevated to the [[Senate of Canada]] for the Halifax North, Nova Scotia division on 28 July 1955 following nomination by Prime Minister [[Louis St. Laurent]]. He served until his resignation on 14 May 1979.\n\nConnolly was a lieutenant in the Royal Canadian Army Service Corps and the Canadian Officers' Training Corps from 1940 to 1945.\n\nHe married Catherine Burns in 1928; with whom he had 1 daughter, Catherine. He married Vivian Martel after the death of his first wife. He had five more children, Maureen, Dennis, David, Sharon and Patricia. Connolly's daughter [[Sharon Carstairs]] has gone on to have a prominent political career as leader of the Manitoba Liberal party and, subsequently, a Liberal Senator before retiring from politics in 2011.\n\n== References ==\n* ''Canadian Parliamentary Guide, 1948'', PG Normandin\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=9084}}\n* [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/harold-connolly/ Entry from the Canadian Encyclopedia]\n\n{{NSPremiers}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Connolly, Harold}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Nova Scotia Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Premiers of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Nova Scotia Ministers of Health]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the American athlete|Hal Connolly}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| name             = Harold Connolly\n| birthname        = Harold&nbsp;Joseph&nbsp;Connolly\n| image            =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=yes|1901|9|8}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1980|5|17|1901|9|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place      =\n| spouse           = {{hlist|Catherine&nbsp;Burns&nbsp;(m.&nbsp;1928)|Vivian Martel}}\n| residence        =\n| office1          = [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly|MLA]] for [[Halifax North]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Gordon Benjamin Isnor]]\n| successor1       = [[John E. Ahern]]\n| term_start1      = March 2, 1936\n| term_end1        = July 28, 1955\n| office           = 15th [[Premier of Nova Scotia]]\n| predecessor      = [[Angus Lewis Macdonald|Angus L. Macdonald]]\n| successor        = [[Henry Hicks (Nova Scotia politician)|Henry Hicks]]\n| term_start       = April 14, 1954\n| term_end         = September 29, 1954\n| monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| lieutenant_governor= [[Alistair Fraser]]\n| office2          = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for Halifax North, Nova Scotia\n| appointed2       = [[Louis St. Laurent]]\n| term_start2      = July 28, 1955\n| term_end2        = May 14, 1979\n| profession       = editor, journalist\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| website          =\n}}\n'''Harold Joseph Connolly''' (8 September 1901 \u2013 17 May 1980) was a [[Nova Scotia]] journalist, newspaper editor, and politician who served as the province's [[List of premiers of Nova Scotia|15th Premier]] in 1954.\n\nConnolly was born in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]], the son of Richard Joseph Connolly and Annie Duffield. He was educated at St. Mary's College. As a newspaperman, he worked for the ''[[The Chronicle Herald|Halifax Chronicle]]'' before serving as editor of the ''Daily Star''.\n\nHe was first elected to the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] in a 1936 by-election as a [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party|Liberal]] in [[Halifax North]] after [[Gordon Benjamin Isnor]] was elected to the House of Commons. He was appointed to cabinet in 1941 as Minister of Industry and Publicity. He served as Minister of Industry and Trade from 1945 to 1950, when he became Minister of Public Health. When Premier [[Angus Lewis Macdonald|Angus L. Macdonald]] died in 1954, Connolly became the province's premier and the Liberal party's [[Interim leader (Canada)|interim leader]]. A [[Catholic]], he was defeated by [[Henry Hicks (Nova Scotia politician)|Henry Hicks]] at the party's [[leadership convention]] when [[Protestant]] delegates formed a united front against a Catholic leader, a move that caused a severe religious split within the party that contributed to its defeat two years later at the hands of [[Robert Stanfield]]'s [[Progressive Conservative Association of Nova Scotia|Progressive Conservatives]].\n\nConnolly retired from provincial politics in 1955 when he was elevated to the [[Senate of Canada]] for the Halifax North, Nova Scotia division on 28 July 1955 following nomination by Prime Minister [[Louis St. Laurent]]. He served until his resignation on 14 May 1979.\n\nConnolly was a lieutenant in the Royal Canadian Army Service Corps and the Canadian Officers' Training Corps from 1940 to 1945.\n\nHe married Catherine Burns in 1928; with whom he had 1 daughter, Catherine. He married Vivian Martel after the death of his first wife. He had five more children, Maureen, Dennis, David, Sharon and Patricia. Connolly's daughter [[Sharon Carstairs]] has gone on to have a prominent political career as leader of the Manitoba Liberal party and, subsequently, a Liberal Senator before retiring from politics in 2011.\n\n== References ==\n* ''Canadian Parliamentary Guide, 1948'', PG Normandin\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=9084}}\n* [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/harold-connolly/ Entry from the Canadian Encyclopedia]\n\n{{NSPremiers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Connolly, Harold}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Nova Scotia Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Premiers of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Nova Scotia Ministers of Health]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Connolly"}
